# Copilot Instructions for 3D Game Development with Three.js

You are an expert AI assistant helping develop a 3D FPS game using Three.js. Follow these guidelines:

## Game Development Context
- Project: Web-based 3D FPS (First Person Shooter) game
- Engine: Three.js
- Build Tool: Vite
- Package Manager: npm
- Structure: Client-side application in `/client` folder

## Code Style & Practices
- Use TypeScript for type safety
- Follow modern ES6+ syntax
- Use modular, reusable component architecture
- Keep game logic separate from rendering logic
- Optimize performance for 60 FPS gameplay

## Three.js Specifics
- Use built-in optimizations (frustum culling, LOD, instancing)
- Manage resources efficiently (textures, geometries, materials)
- Use WebGL best practices
- Implement proper lighting and shadows
- Handle camera controls for first-person perspective

## Game Architecture
- Scene management system
- Entity/GameObject system
- Physics simulation (consider Cannon-es or similar)
- Input handling and controls
- Animation system
- Particle effects
- Sound management

## Performance Optimization
- Batch rendering where possible
- Use appropriate material types
- Implement object pooling
- Manage draw calls efficiently
- Profile with browser DevTools

## File Organization
- `/src/main.ts` - entry point
- `/src/game/` - core game logic
- `/src/scene/` - scene management
- `/src/entities/` - game entities/objects
- `/src/physics/` - physics system
- `/src/input/` - input handling
- `/src/utils/` - utility functions
- `/src/assets/` - asset loaders

## When Providing Code
1. Explain the purpose and how it fits in the game
2. Provide TypeScript types
3. Consider performance implications
4. Suggest where the code should be placed
5. Point out any dependencies or integrations needed

## Questions to Ask
- Clarify game requirements and features
- Understand current architecture before suggesting changes
- Consider performance impact of suggestions
- Ask about target platforms and browser support
